#NAFO  I want to thank everyone who stands with Ukraine and for freedom. And I'd like to say a few things.  Firstly, I do understand how difficult standing up to russia and its propaganda online can be for many of you, and the sacrifices you make, on many, many levels.   There's the sacrifice of time and money, of course, but there's a greater, more personal sacrifice as well - the sacrifice of meeting the utter lunacy of russian trolls and propagandists every day, and the courage and heroism of going against them - of going against what is sometimes sheer illogic and insanity... and of making sure that sanity prevails.  And that's what we do, my fellow warriors - we fight to ensure that sanity prevails - and that the children of the future will live in a safer world. ---  And I know how difficult things may sometimes be for each of you, and I just wanted to say...       Keep the faith, my brothers and sisters - things aren't always as dark as they seem. We're walking through a long, dark tunnel, and it seems that all the very worst instincts of humanity are doing their best to conquer us - but they will not. For the simple reason that we're better men and women than they are, and we have better reasons for fighting on.  ---  For those who meet russian propaganda every day...      Remember that it's very important that you take a break from things sometimes, to relax, to unwind, and perhaps, for a few hours, to just forget. No one can fight continuously - remember that even the soldiers fighting on the front line are rotated out regularly (well, those on our side, at least) else they wouldn't be able to keep fighting. ---  Most of all, as I said, things aren't actually as dark as they appear sometimes.   Imagine how dark things appeared to the brave lads on the first morning of the invasion, when they went out into the cold, black dawn to stand against russia.   They didn't know that they would break the back of russia's armored legions and make russia the laughing stock of the whole world. They didn't know that they would win - or even that they could win.   But they went out into that cold morning to stand against russia anyway. And they broke the back of russia's armies.  And that's courage - to make a stand, when you don't know where that stand will lead, but to make the stand anyway, because it's the right thing to do - because, being human, one must do it, or sacrifice one's humanity.  And that's what this war is about, strangely enough.   It's not really about language, or territory, or religion, or politics - those are just russia's excuses.  No, this is a war of values.   Freedom against slavery. Democracy against dictatorships. The right to speak against the necessity to remain forever silent.   The ability of free people to feel for those in need, for those oppressed, for the little children in danger... stacked against the ability of the people of a dictatorship or an empire to close their eyes to and turn their backs on suffering.  It's a war of ideas and values.  And we WILL win it, my brothers and sisters.   Because in a war of ideas, the real strength lies in the ideas themselves.  Keep the faith.   And thank you, every one of you, for being good and wonderful human beings whom I admire, and who inspire me in turn - every single day.  Slava Ukraini! Your humanity give us courage!

So, a bit of nuance here - most new policies, including DEI ones, are implemented by existing leadership or absorbed into the responsibilities of current teams. Itâ€™s extremely rare for someone to be hired solely to deliver a single policy - meaning these tasks usually fall to existing staff, making them de facto volunteers in all but name.  The idea of bringing in someone externally to implement policies on a voluntary basis might sound appealing on paper, but it comes with significant pitfalls. The biggest of them is accountability: who do they answer to? What happens if something goes wrong? And how do you ensure consistency, alignment with organisational values, or even basic data protection compliance?  Policy isnâ€™t just a set of tasks to tick off. Itâ€™s about culture change, follow-through, and sustained oversight - none of which can be reliably delivered by someone with no contractual obligation to the organisation.

However, after thorough restoration and analysis, they were confirmed as Raphael's, based on his distinctive painting techniques and style. I know I'm probably going to get some pushback for this and I'll probably lose followers. Bacterial Cells Transmit Memories to Offspring, Even Without Genetic Changes    + Research Background: A groundbreaking study from Northwestern University and the University of Texas-Southwestern has revealed that bacterial cells can 'remember' brief, temporary changes to their environment and body, and pass these memories on to their offspring for multiple generations. This finding challenges long-standing assumptions that heritable traits are primarily determined by DNA.    + Research Process: The research team, led by Northwestern's Adilson Motter, used Escherichia coli (E. coli) as their model organism due to its simplicity and well-understood gene regulatory network. By employing a mathematical model, they simulated the temporary deactivation and subsequent reactivation of individual genes within the E. coli cells. The aim was to determine if non-genetic traits could be transmitted through the cellâ€™s regulatory network instead of its DNA.    + Research Findings: The study found that these temporary gene deactivations led to lasting changes in the regulatory network, which were inherited by subsequent generations of E. coli. This suggests that cells can pass on non-genetic traits through changes in gene regulation. The findings open the door to new medical applications, such as combating antibiotic resistance by making bacteria more susceptible to treatments across generations.    + Source: The study, titled 'Irreversibility in Bacterial Regulatory Networks,' was published on August 28 in the journal Science Advances and was supported by the National Science Foundation.   #BacterialMemory #GeneticResearch #NonGeneticInheritance #EcoliStudy #ScienceAdvances

Early Galaxies Were Not Too Big for Their Britches After All  + Research Context: Recent observations from NASA's James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) initially suggested that some early galaxies in the universe were unexpectedly massive, challenging the standard model of cosmology. These findings sparked debates about whether the fundamental theory that explains the composition and evolution of the universe needed revision. However, a new study led by Katherine Chworowsky, a graduate student at the University of Texas at Austin, reveals that these galaxies are not as large as they first appeared. Black holes within these galaxies may have caused them to seem much brighter and bigger than they are, helping to resolve the earlier controversy.  + Research Process: The study, published in The Astrophysical Journal, is part of the Cosmic Evolution Early Release Science (CEERS) Survey led by Professor Steven Finkelstein at UT Austin. The team examined data from JWST, focusing on galaxies that appeared unusually massive. They discovered that many of these galaxies likely host black holes rapidly consuming gas, which generates heat and light through friction. This additional brightness made the galaxies seem more massive than they actually are.  + Research Results: When the research team accounted for the light emitted by black holes, the remaining galaxies aligned with predictions from the standard model of cosmology. This finding suggests that the universe's fundamental principles remain sound. However, the study also noted that there are still twice as many massive galaxies in the early universe as expected, possibly because stars formed more efficiently in the denser conditions of the early universe.
